commit.message:
connections.py: Split out get_timestamp, add timeptamp param to fetch_file, fetch_content

This allows for more fine-grained use.
Gkeys is moving to a sandboxed seeds update.  This allows to use the installed seed file 
timestamp, while still downloading a new file and saving the new timestamp to an 
__updates__ subdir.  Only after that file has been verified will it then replace the installed 
seed file and timestamp.

connections.py: Reset fetch_content() ref-fetch timeout to False

The fetch_content() only returns true if there is new content.
Unlike fetch_file that only returns False for an actual failure.
Problem reported by Justin Lecher <jlec>

Fix the re-fetch cycle timeout returning False when it should have returned True

If the recycle timeout had not expired, consumer apps got a failure result, instead of success.
Add a warning message indicating the re-fetch cylce timeout and remaining time left.

Flesh out remianing logging output types

Make these changes backwards API consumer compatible by defaulting to 'error' mode.
Improve existing output messages to take advantage of the change.
Include 'SSL-fetch' identifier for error messages so the source is known.
Fix another incidence of a trailing \n causing a timetamp header error
Version Bump for a release

connections.py: Fix commit 99f763ed2f for when a tpath does not exist

The verify_cycle was being done too late in the code.  It needed to be first.
When it was done, the connection was already established and so a timestamp already
existed, but no timestamp file did.
This caused the code to traceback due to a non-existent path.
connections.py: Add optional verify_only parameter to toggle updating the timestamp file time

connections.py: Adds compatibility parameter to utime() call

In order to update the mtime of a timestamp file, the os.utime()
function is called. In py3 variants, simply calling "os.utime(<file>)"
is enough to update the mtime. However, in py2.7, you need to also pass
None as a parameter for it to set the mtime as the current system time.
As this also works in all py3 versions there is no need to check
versions for compatibility.
